00:05:50.408 --> 00:05:52.244
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:54.164 --> 00:05:55.080
ANDY PRATT: All right.

00:05:55.080 --> 00:05:56.140
Thank you, Thushan.

00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:56.940
So I'm Andy.

00:05:56.940 --> 00:06:00.410
And I am also officially fun.

00:06:00.410 --> 00:06:02.670
And what I would like
to do is talk to you

00:06:02.670 --> 00:06:06.280
about the building blocks of
great conversational gameplay.

00:06:06.280 --> 00:06:08.580
So there's going to be
unique challenges that

00:06:08.580 --> 00:06:10.680
make designing
conversational games very

00:06:10.680 --> 00:06:13.800
different than your console,
PC, or mobile games.

00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:16.410
And so here are some
of the principles

00:06:16.410 --> 00:06:20.580
that our team uses to deliver
engaging experiences that users

00:06:20.580 --> 00:06:22.490
love.

00:06:22.490 --> 00:06:25.550
First, we need to
create the universe.

00:06:25.550 --> 00:06:27.740
Think of some of
your favorite games.

00:06:27.740 --> 00:06:30.830
What are the worlds that
they transport you to?

00:06:30.830 --> 00:06:32.540
Some of my old
school favorites are

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:36.320
things like "Dark Castle," and
"Space Quest," and "Zelda."

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:38.660
And there's this
orchestration of elements

00:06:38.660 --> 00:06:41.570
through the backgrounds,
the characters, the story,

00:06:41.570 --> 00:06:42.950
the sounds.

00:06:42.950 --> 00:06:44.900
They all work together.

00:06:44.900 --> 00:06:50.720
But they often rely on visuals
to bring this world to life.

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:52.390
Now with conversational
games, we

00:06:52.390 --> 00:06:55.420
don't always have those
elements to work with.

00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:57.880
So we need to look for
inspiration elsewhere.

00:06:57.880 --> 00:07:00.130
And one of the places
that we can look

00:07:00.130 --> 00:07:02.950
is the oral
storytelling techniques

00:07:02.950 --> 00:07:05.050
that go back hundreds of years.

00:07:05.050 --> 00:07:08.810
So a simple story-starting
phrase like "once upon a time"

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:12.550
helps set the stage in fairy
tales, fables, and myths.

00:07:12.550 --> 00:07:16.030
And the origins date
back past the 1400s.

00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:18.430
They're also pretty
much universal.

00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:21.040
You can find equivalents
in dozens of languages--

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:26.720
so things like "a long time
ago" or "there once lived."

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:29.030
So for us to create
our universe,

00:07:29.030 --> 00:07:32.510
we need to set the stage
just like "once upon a time"

00:07:32.510 --> 00:07:34.460
does for fairy tales.

00:07:34.460 --> 00:07:36.140
It doesn't need
to be much, but it

00:07:36.140 --> 00:07:39.870
does help users understand
the world they are in.

00:07:39.870 --> 00:07:41.760
So here's a quick example.

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:44.700
If you asked the Assistant
what should I be for Halloween,

00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:47.150
it's going to go through
a series of questions

00:07:47.150 --> 00:07:50.360
and help you decide a silly
costume that you should wear

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:52.130
when you go trick or treating.

00:07:52.130 --> 00:07:54.620
So here are two
approaches on how we can

00:07:54.620 --> 00:07:56.330
bring the player into the game.

00:07:56.330 --> 00:07:59.107
Let's listen to the first one.

00:07:59.107 --> 00:08:01.440
GOOGLE ASSISTANT: Welcome to
the Halloween costume quiz.

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:03.240
Answer these five
questions to find out

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:06.284
what you should be for
Halloween this year.

00:08:06.284 --> 00:08:07.200
ANDY PRATT: All right.

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:09.420
So that technically
does the job.

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:11.850
It brings the user
in a little bit.

00:08:11.850 --> 00:08:14.820
It also at least gives feedback
to let users know that they've

00:08:14.820 --> 00:08:16.140
entered the right game.

00:08:16.140 --> 00:08:17.650
But I think we can do more.

00:08:17.650 --> 00:08:20.890
So now let's listen
to this second option.

00:08:20.890 --> 00:08:23.170
GOOGLE ASSISTANT: Wow,
I'm so glad you asked.

00:08:23.170 --> 00:08:24.800
I don't want to
toot my own horn,

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:26.241
but I'm kind of an expert.

00:08:26.241 --> 00:08:26.740
[DOORBELL]

00:08:26.740 --> 00:08:28.090
Oh, hold on.

00:08:28.090 --> 00:08:28.990
[GROAN]

00:08:28.990 --> 00:08:30.160
CHILDREN: Trick or treat!

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:31.690
GOOGLE ASSISTANT: Nice costumes.

00:08:31.690 --> 00:08:33.390
Great use of burlap.

00:08:33.390 --> 00:08:33.909
Here you go.

00:08:33.909 --> 00:08:34.570
CHILDREN: Thank you.

00:08:34.570 --> 00:08:36.104
GOOGLE ASSISTANT: OK,
run along and have fun.

00:08:36.104 --> 00:08:36.409
CHILDREN: Thank you.

00:08:36.409 --> 00:08:38.284
GOOGLE ASSISTANT: I need
to help someone now.

00:08:38.284 --> 00:08:39.594
CHILDREN: Bye.

00:08:39.594 --> 00:08:42.010
GOOGLE ASSISTANT: OK, let me
assess your costume interests

00:08:42.010 --> 00:08:43.460
with a few questions.

00:08:43.460 --> 00:08:44.950
Are you ready?

00:08:44.950 --> 00:08:47.500
ANDY PRATT: So listen to how
that second version really

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:49.180
starts to set the stage.

00:08:49.180 --> 00:08:50.920
And more importantly,
it gets users

00:08:50.920 --> 00:08:52.550
excited about playing the game.

00:08:57.180 --> 00:08:59.660
So the other thing that
we really need to do

00:08:59.660 --> 00:09:03.380
is to kind of look on ways
to layer in sound design.

00:09:03.380 --> 00:09:05.720
It's such a critical element,
especially since we have

00:09:05.720 --> 00:09:08.040
fewer elements to work with.

00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:11.810
So we want to look at ways to
kind of paint this audio world.

00:09:11.810 --> 00:09:13.720
Now this can be done
in a couple of ways.

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:15.680
One is kind of through
the background,

00:09:15.680 --> 00:09:18.710
so music or atmosphere
to kind of really

00:09:18.710 --> 00:09:21.110
help create that whole effect.

00:09:21.110 --> 00:09:23.430
Or we can also use it
as a foreground element.

00:09:23.430 --> 00:09:25.100
So maybe we want
to use it as a way

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:27.020
to give feedback to
the user that they've

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:28.610
done something right or wrong.

00:09:28.610 --> 00:09:31.220
Or we want to use it to
emphasize key moments

00:09:31.220 --> 00:09:34.010
of delights or dialogue.

00:09:34.010 --> 00:09:37.100
To illustrate this point,
the Google Assistant

00:09:37.100 --> 00:09:39.020
has a poem for you--

00:09:39.020 --> 00:09:40.640
our loving audience.

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:43.190
It's titled "Bike
and Kickstands.

00:09:43.190 --> 00:09:45.122
So let's listen to this.

00:09:45.122 --> 00:09:46.830
GOOGLE ASSISTANT:
Thanks for humoring me.

00:09:46.830 --> 00:09:48.930
Just give me a few
seconds to write it down.

00:09:48.930 --> 00:09:51.150
You're like a bike and
I'm like the kickstand.

00:09:51.150 --> 00:09:53.580
Lean on me, friend, when
it's time to make plans.

00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:55.110
Whether you're
searching for info,

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:56.820
trying to spell
"chateau," looking

00:09:56.820 --> 00:10:00.894
for recipes or other
necessities, I'll always reply.

00:10:00.894 --> 00:10:01.810
ANDY PRATT: All right.

00:10:01.810 --> 00:10:03.280
So pretty good.

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:06.422
Now, let's hear it with
some sound layered in.

00:10:06.422 --> 00:10:08.130
GOOGLE ASSISTANT:
Thanks for humoring me.

00:10:08.130 --> 00:10:10.635
Just give me a few
seconds to write it down.

00:10:10.635 --> 00:10:11.940
[PENCIL SCRIBBLING]

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:13.250
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:10:13.250 --> 00:10:15.320
You're like a bike and
I'm like the kickstand.

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:17.030
[BIKE BELL]

00:10:17.030 --> 00:10:20.240
Lean on me, friend, when
it's time to make plans.

00:10:20.240 --> 00:10:21.770
Whether you're
searching for info,

00:10:21.770 --> 00:10:24.170
trying to spell "chateau,"
looking for recipes

00:10:24.170 --> 00:10:26.880
or other necessities, if
you have any questions,

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:29.342
I'll always reply.

00:10:29.342 --> 00:10:30.550
ANDY PRATT: Do you feel that?

00:10:30.550 --> 00:10:31.870
It's right here.

00:10:31.870 --> 00:10:33.030
It's deep inside.

00:10:33.030 --> 00:10:35.920
It really just helps
elevate everything.

00:10:35.920 --> 00:10:39.730
And so fortunately, later
on in our wonderful program,

00:10:39.730 --> 00:10:41.590
we are going to
show you how to add

00:10:41.590 --> 00:10:43.290
the love into your dialogue.

00:10:46.270 --> 00:10:48.200
Now, another thing
to consider is

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:51.500
how to use sound to
get users to focus.

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:54.870
This can be especially helpful
in multiplayer experiences.

00:10:54.870 --> 00:10:57.140
So in our game, "Are
you feeling lucky,"

00:10:57.140 --> 00:10:59.210
users are automatically
given names.

00:10:59.210 --> 00:11:01.880
And since you can have up
to six players at a time,

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:04.430
we found through our research
that users might forget

00:11:04.430 --> 00:11:06.140
when it's their turn to answer.

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:11.780
So to help get users to focus,
we pair them with audio cues.

00:11:11.780 --> 00:11:13.250
So let's listen
to how that works.

00:11:18.114 --> 00:11:20.280
GOOGLE ASSISTANT: OK, just
so everybody is straight,

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:22.260
I'll give you your names again.

00:11:22.260 --> 00:11:23.430
They are Nibbler,

00:11:23.430 --> 00:11:24.210
[QUACK]

00:11:24.210 --> 00:11:24.750
Scooter,

00:11:24.750 --> 00:11:25.770
[FLUTE]

00:11:25.770 --> 00:11:26.490
Freestyle,

00:11:26.490 --> 00:11:27.210
[RECORD SCRATCH]

00:11:27.210 --> 00:11:27.960
and Puddles.

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:29.079
[WATER DRIP]

00:11:29.079 --> 00:11:30.870
ANDY PRATT: So this
can be a great way just

00:11:30.870 --> 00:11:34.380
to kind of associate that
audio cue with that name,

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:35.400
bring users back.

00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:36.450
And it's something
that you guys might

00:11:36.450 --> 00:11:38.640
want to consider as you're
developing games too.

00:11:38.640 --> 00:11:41.190
How can you use audio cues
to get users to focus?

