Now, our next principle
is to keep it simple.

00:11:50.380 --> 00:11:53.020
Conversations-- they're
inherently linear.

00:11:53.020 --> 00:11:54.860
And it's really easy
to move forwards,

00:11:54.860 --> 00:11:57.110
but it's much
harder to move back.

00:11:57.110 --> 00:12:00.110
We can't ask users to hold
too much in their heads.

00:12:00.110 --> 00:12:05.370
So here are a few ways that
you can keep things simple.

00:12:05.370 --> 00:12:08.990
The first is use a
consistent structure.

00:12:08.990 --> 00:12:12.860
Familiarity is going to make
people feel more comfortable.

00:12:12.860 --> 00:12:15.080
And the more we have
deviations, it's

00:12:15.080 --> 00:12:17.960
going to increase the
cognitive load of that player

00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:23.500
and risk to a higher level of
confusion and possibly errors.

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:26.260
So imagine this--
we're in a quiz.

00:12:26.260 --> 00:12:29.410
And here are just two
different questions,

00:12:29.410 --> 00:12:31.368
pretty similar in structure.

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:38.340
Now, we restate that question.

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:40.620
And then, we follow
up with the options.

00:12:40.620 --> 00:12:43.630
So we still kind of can vary
the language a little bit,

00:12:43.630 --> 00:12:46.344
but you can see the
structure is very consistent.

00:12:46.344 --> 00:12:48.260
And as the player goes
through the experience,

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:50.370
they're now going to
know what to expect,

00:12:50.370 --> 00:12:53.340
allowing them to focus on
the content and not the game

00:12:53.340 --> 00:12:54.510
mechanics.

00:12:54.510 --> 00:12:58.530
Now, as we push the boundaries
of conversational gameplay,

00:12:58.530 --> 00:13:00.150
you may want to
change the structure.

00:13:00.150 --> 00:13:02.160
So maybe you want to
have like a bonus round

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:03.930
or something like that.

00:13:03.930 --> 00:13:06.750
That's going to be OK as
long as you take the time

00:13:06.750 --> 00:13:09.600
and teach the users that
this portion of the game

00:13:09.600 --> 00:13:10.840
is going to be different.

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:13.410
So you're going to need to
ultimately weigh is that worth

00:13:13.410 --> 00:13:13.910
it.

00:13:13.910 --> 00:13:17.367
Is it worth it to take that
time in order to explain it,

00:13:17.367 --> 00:13:19.200
even though it may slow
the pace down a bit?

00:13:21.790 --> 00:13:24.040
Now, another simple
thing to keep in mind

00:13:24.040 --> 00:13:26.860
is when you list out the
choices for a player,

00:13:26.860 --> 00:13:30.252
just make sure you follow
up with the exact order.

00:13:30.252 --> 00:13:31.210
So if we look at this--

00:13:31.210 --> 00:13:34.330
would you rather
travel on a tiny plane

00:13:34.330 --> 00:13:37.851
or a surfboard-- we follow up
with plane and then surfboard.

00:13:37.851 --> 00:13:39.850
Sometimes it's easy just
to kind of switch those

00:13:39.850 --> 00:13:41.711
around, but keep it consistent.

00:13:44.420 --> 00:13:47.420
Our next principle is
to keep players engaged.

00:13:47.420 --> 00:13:51.390
We don't want your games
to feel like a lecture.

00:13:51.390 --> 00:13:56.910
It's very easy for players to
lose focus and get distracted.

00:13:56.910 --> 00:13:58.950
One way to do this
is by analyzing

00:13:58.950 --> 00:14:01.870
the player's experience
over the course of the game.

00:14:01.870 --> 00:14:03.930
So some of you kind of
coming from the game world

00:14:03.930 --> 00:14:06.630
may be familiar with the
player interest curve, which

00:14:06.630 --> 00:14:10.350
is essentially a way to
represent the highlights

00:14:10.350 --> 00:14:13.380
and lowlights of a
player's experience.

00:14:13.380 --> 00:14:15.270
And this is going to
be similar to kind

00:14:15.270 --> 00:14:16.567
of creating user journey maps.

00:14:16.567 --> 00:14:18.150
If you're familiar
with product design

00:14:18.150 --> 00:14:21.215
and done some of that, kind
of similar types of concepts.

00:14:21.215 --> 00:14:22.590
You're just simply
going to watch

00:14:22.590 --> 00:14:24.480
players playing your game.

00:14:24.480 --> 00:14:27.030
And you're going to
notice key milestones.

00:14:27.030 --> 00:14:28.290
Watch the reactions.

00:14:28.290 --> 00:14:29.160
Are they cringing?

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:30.140
Are they excited?

00:14:30.140 --> 00:14:32.255
And you're going to
start to plot this.

00:14:32.255 --> 00:14:33.630
Now, as you do
this, you're going

00:14:33.630 --> 00:14:35.580
to generate these patterns.

00:14:35.580 --> 00:14:37.560
And as these patterns
happen, you're

00:14:37.560 --> 00:14:40.410
going to want to make
sure that the curve is up.

00:14:40.410 --> 00:14:41.992
So looking at a
graph like this, this

00:14:41.992 --> 00:14:43.200
is a little bit of a concern.

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:45.770
You can see it starts
off with a great intro

00:14:45.770 --> 00:14:49.050
and it ends with an outcome, but
the middle kind of sags a bit.

00:14:49.050 --> 00:14:50.460
And we don't want
that to happen.

00:14:53.940 --> 00:14:56.250
One way to keep
players engaged is

00:14:56.250 --> 00:14:59.810
to make the player part
of the conversation.

00:14:59.810 --> 00:15:02.492
Your experience is going to
be directed by the dialogue,

00:15:02.492 --> 00:15:04.200
so we want to make
sure that we're always

00:15:04.200 --> 00:15:07.170
talking with the player
and not at the player.

00:15:07.170 --> 00:15:10.860
You can do this by
creating digestible chunks.

00:15:10.860 --> 00:15:16.480
You find moments for your
player to participate.

00:15:16.480 --> 00:15:19.660
The other thing that we can
do is respond contextually

00:15:19.660 --> 00:15:21.260
whenever possible.

00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:24.700
Craft your dialogue based
on that player's response.

00:15:24.700 --> 00:15:26.770
So imagine here,
the player is asked

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:30.190
if they would rather play
with a unicorn or a dragon.

00:15:30.190 --> 00:15:33.590
And here we have a
very generic response.

00:15:33.590 --> 00:15:37.970
So this could be something
for any of the questions.

00:15:37.970 --> 00:15:41.000
However in this example, we are
able to respond to something

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.250
that's not only a
bit more delightful,

00:15:43.250 --> 00:15:45.750
but it also makes the
game feel smarter.

00:15:45.750 --> 00:15:48.230
It's providing simple
feedback to the user

00:15:48.230 --> 00:15:50.120
that the game understands
what they said.

00:15:53.830 --> 00:15:57.250
Now, as we move to kind of
more visual experiences--

00:15:57.250 --> 00:15:59.740
smart displays-- what
we're going to want to do

00:15:59.740 --> 00:16:05.650
is avoid transcribing word
for word all of the dialogue.

00:16:05.650 --> 00:16:08.360
So Thushan mentioned
before the BuzzFeed quiz,

00:16:08.360 --> 00:16:09.940
and so here is
kind of an example.

00:16:09.940 --> 00:16:12.330
On the right here, we
see this is the TTS.

00:16:12.330 --> 00:16:15.640
So this is what
the output will be.

00:16:15.640 --> 00:16:18.530
On the left is more of
the experience itself.

00:16:18.530 --> 00:16:21.400
So you can see we're not
just using the screen just

00:16:21.400 --> 00:16:22.930
to throw all that text in.

00:16:22.930 --> 00:16:24.160
We want to simplify it.

00:16:24.160 --> 00:16:25.690
We want to move
the user forward.

00:16:25.690 --> 00:16:28.780
We want to use the screen
to create that universe.

00:16:28.780 --> 00:16:31.390
We also want to just make
sure there's opportunities

00:16:31.390 --> 00:16:34.660
to increase the brand and create
more of an emotional connection

00:16:34.660 --> 00:16:35.750
with the user.

00:16:35.750 --> 00:16:38.340
So don't transcribe
your text word for word.

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:43.340
Another way to keep
players engaged

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:46.340
is to have a great payoff.

00:16:46.340 --> 00:16:48.800
Our users' time is very
valuable and there's

00:16:48.800 --> 00:16:50.780
a lot of competition
for it, so we

00:16:50.780 --> 00:16:54.177
need to make sure that we reward
them for getting to the end.

00:16:54.177 --> 00:16:55.760
So if you remember
that interest curve

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:58.610
that I was showing you before,
it ended on that high note.

00:16:58.610 --> 00:17:00.490
You guys, as game
designers, are going

00:17:00.490 --> 00:17:03.440
to need to figure out what
that payoff is going to be.

00:17:06.599 --> 00:17:11.240
All right, our last principle
is to always be playtesting.

00:17:11.240 --> 00:17:14.099
Now in the game industry,
this is nothing new.

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:16.250
We know that it's going
to help increase quality.

00:17:16.250 --> 00:17:21.050
We know it's going to help find
bugs and basic design flaws.

00:17:21.050 --> 00:17:23.720
We also know that engagement
is going to drop off

00:17:23.720 --> 00:17:25.550
if the game feels broken.

00:17:25.550 --> 00:17:28.109
And we should expect that
errors are going to happen.

00:17:28.109 --> 00:17:29.730
Especially with
conversational games,

00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:32.960
we know that players can
respond with anything.

00:17:32.960 --> 00:17:34.820
The environment may be
polluted-- just kind

00:17:34.820 --> 00:17:36.247
of full of background noise.

00:17:36.247 --> 00:17:38.330
We definitely got a bit
of that as we were kind of

00:17:38.330 --> 00:17:41.260
in the sandbox, and you can kind
of hear all the people around.

00:17:41.260 --> 00:17:43.010
There's going to be
situations like that--

00:17:43.010 --> 00:17:44.150
if you're at a party--

00:17:44.150 --> 00:17:45.170
where it might be tough.

00:17:45.170 --> 00:17:47.300
So we have to
anticipate some of that.

00:17:47.300 --> 00:17:51.260
We also know that players
may forget what to do next.

00:17:51.260 --> 00:17:53.120
A few common errors
that we see are

00:17:53.120 --> 00:17:55.100
going to be things
like no input errors,

00:17:55.100 --> 00:17:58.530
where the Assistant just hasn't
detected a response at all.

00:17:58.530 --> 00:18:00.440
We also see things
like no match errors,

00:18:00.440 --> 00:18:03.740
where maybe the Assistant
can't understand the reply.

00:18:03.740 --> 00:18:06.080
And we also get
false accept errors,

00:18:06.080 --> 00:18:08.840
so this might be where the
Assistant misunderstands

00:18:08.840 --> 00:18:11.810
the user, but just kind
of moves along anyway.

00:18:11.810 --> 00:18:14.960
So here's a few things that we
can do to minimize those errors

00:18:14.960 --> 00:18:18.130
and maximize the fun.

00:18:18.130 --> 00:18:20.950
One, start with your concept.

00:18:20.950 --> 00:18:23.380
And you can do this
in a very low-fi way.

00:18:23.380 --> 00:18:28.810
So have a users, players, read
a script of the happy path,

00:18:28.810 --> 00:18:32.080
or essentially the ideal
path of the game play.

00:18:32.080 --> 00:18:35.020
You need to make sure that
the gameplay is actually fun.

00:18:35.020 --> 00:18:37.000
If the happy path
isn't happy, then it

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.550
might be time to look at
ways to iterate on it.

00:18:42.530 --> 00:18:46.210
Another thing we do is we like
to test with our eyes closed.

00:18:46.210 --> 00:18:48.970
So these are
conversational games.

00:18:48.970 --> 00:18:51.850
And you start by
designing with voice only.

00:18:51.850 --> 00:18:53.880
You can do this with
a working prototype,

00:18:53.880 --> 00:18:56.410
so something like dialogue
flow, or you can also

00:18:56.410 --> 00:18:58.660
do this as like a
"Wizard of Oz" technique

00:18:58.660 --> 00:19:00.310
where a team member
maybe simulate

00:19:00.310 --> 00:19:02.200
the response of the
system, and you kind of

00:19:02.200 --> 00:19:04.810
have it set up in this
controlled environment.

00:19:04.810 --> 00:19:09.340
This is a great way to help
test the content, the pacing,

00:19:09.340 --> 00:19:11.440
and the complexity of
your game mechanics.

00:19:14.050 --> 00:19:18.670
Now, the last suggestion
here is to test

00:19:18.670 --> 00:19:22.360
with a range of audiences, not
just your primary demographic.

00:19:22.360 --> 00:19:24.430
So watch your
parents play with it.

00:19:24.430 --> 00:19:26.020
Watch your kids play with it.

00:19:26.020 --> 00:19:29.470
They may bubble up issues with
comprehension and complexity

00:19:29.470 --> 00:19:30.670
of your dialogue.

00:19:30.670 --> 00:19:36.120
They may discover that some
words are just hard to say.

00:19:36.120 --> 00:19:39.750
So to wrap up really quick, some
of the basic building blocks

00:19:39.750 --> 00:19:44.490
that our team uses are create
the universe, keep it simple,

00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:48.670
keep users engaged, and
constantly playtest.

00:19:48.670 --> 00:19:52.760
Now, I'm going to
hand it over to Ralfi.

00:19:52.760 --> 00:19:54.760
[APPLAUSE]

00:19:56.609 --> 00:19:57.900
RALFI NAHMIAS: Hello, everyone.

00:19:57.900 --> 00:20:02.210
This is Ralfi, who is also
fun, from Dialogflow team.

00:20:02.210 --> 00:20:04.490
Now that you are equipped
with the expert tips

00:20:04.490 --> 00:20:06.860
from Andy, let's dive
into how we can actually

00:20:06.860 --> 00:20:09.010
implement all of this.

00:20:09.010 --> 00:20:11.444
The good news is starting
is really simple.

00:20:11.444 --> 00:20:13.110
We are working really
hard on developing

00:20:13.110 --> 00:20:15.840
tools and capabilities to make
it easier for you to focus

00:20:15.840 --> 00:20:17.250
on what you do the best--

00:20:17.250 --> 00:20:19.990
developing games.

00:20:19.990 --> 00:20:22.420
At the high level,
developing actions for Google

00:20:22.420 --> 00:20:23.740
has three main components.

00:20:23.740 --> 00:20:27.010
This applies to any kind of
actions-- games or non-games.

00:20:27.010 --> 00:20:28.480
The first step is
you need to build

00:20:28.480 --> 00:20:30.210
your conversational flows.

00:20:30.210 --> 00:20:33.310
Then, you need to connect
your conversational flow

00:20:33.310 --> 00:20:34.720
to your game logic.

00:20:34.720 --> 00:20:36.880
And lastly, you need
to publish your actions

00:20:36.880 --> 00:20:38.700
to Google Assistant.

00:20:38.700 --> 00:20:40.300
For the rest of this
talk, I am going

00:20:40.300 --> 00:20:44.050
to focus on Dialogflow, our
industry-leading conversational

00:20:44.050 --> 00:20:46.540
agent platform-- creation
platform-- and actions

00:20:46.540 --> 00:20:49.120
on Google Console, which
is the tool that you

00:20:49.120 --> 00:20:53.960
publish your actions
to Google Assistant.

00:20:53.960 --> 00:20:55.960
Dialogflow is a
tool that makes it

00:20:55.960 --> 00:20:58.720
super easy to build
conversational flows.

00:20:58.720 --> 00:21:01.000
It extracts meaning
from dialogues,

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.190
applying machine learning
to the training examples

00:21:03.190 --> 00:21:04.369
that you provide.

00:21:04.369 --> 00:21:05.660
Let me show you how this works.

00:21:08.290 --> 00:21:11.050
Imagine you said the following
sentence-- "send three

00:21:11.050 --> 00:21:13.120
dragons to England immediately!

00:21:13.120 --> 00:21:15.360
Attack with green
flames for five hours."

00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:22.070
Dialogflow understands that
this is about game term.

00:21:22.070 --> 00:21:24.220
It's not about user
asking for help

00:21:24.220 --> 00:21:26.920
or trying to exit the
game, it's about game term.

00:21:26.920 --> 00:21:29.380
It also identifies
important concepts

00:21:29.380 --> 00:21:31.870
within this piece of dialogue.

00:21:31.870 --> 00:21:34.030
It understands common
concepts like numbers,

00:21:34.030 --> 00:21:35.860
countries, colors.

00:21:35.860 --> 00:21:39.910
It can also extract specific
concepts about your game,

00:21:39.910 --> 00:21:42.730
like characters and weapons.

00:21:42.730 --> 00:21:45.760
It's smart enough to understand
some more complex concepts

00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:47.560
like time, which is relative.

00:21:47.560 --> 00:21:49.690
In this example, when
you say five hours,

00:21:49.690 --> 00:21:52.540
it resolves it from the
time that the sentence

00:21:52.540 --> 00:21:54.310
was uttered to 5 hours later.

00:21:56.890 --> 00:21:58.390
And the cool thing
about Dialogflow

00:21:58.390 --> 00:22:01.420
is it comes with built-in
internationalization support.

00:22:01.420 --> 00:22:03.460
With just a few clicks,
you can replicate

00:22:03.460 --> 00:22:06.519
the same conversational
flow in another language.

00:22:06.519 --> 00:22:08.310
If you want to learn
more about Dialogflow,

00:22:08.310 --> 00:22:10.510
you can attend a
dedicated session on it

00:22:10.510 --> 00:22:11.890
at 3:30 on stage two.

00:22:14.590 --> 00:22:17.710
Now that you've built your
actions, it's time to test.

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:19.720
Up until now, you could
only test your actions

00:22:19.720 --> 00:22:22.570
using your own developer
account on devices

00:22:22.570 --> 00:22:25.640
that are associated with that
particular developer account.

00:22:25.640 --> 00:22:28.420
We've just released
a new feature

00:22:28.420 --> 00:22:31.590
that allows you to share your
actions with a set of alpha

00:22:31.590 --> 00:22:34.300
or beta users.

00:22:34.300 --> 00:22:36.640
The alpha release is really
good for testing in design

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:37.900
and development phase.

00:22:37.900 --> 00:22:39.820
There are no policy reviews.

00:22:39.820 --> 00:22:42.310
And that's the quickest
way to get your testers,

00:22:42.310 --> 00:22:45.520
and get feedback, and iterate.

00:22:45.520 --> 00:22:48.340
The beta release is for games
that are ready to launch.

00:22:48.340 --> 00:22:50.530
It goes through
full review process.

00:22:50.530 --> 00:22:53.440
The goal here is to find
edge cases, bugs, and issues

00:22:53.440 --> 00:22:54.670
with final polish.

00:22:54.670 --> 00:22:57.870
Ultimately, we want you to
produce the best game possible.

00:23:00.690 --> 00:23:03.680
After you build,
test, and publish,

00:23:03.680 --> 00:23:06.840
you are effectively part
of the Google ecosystem,

00:23:06.840 --> 00:23:09.060
so you should make
the most out of that.

00:23:09.060 --> 00:23:11.790
The easiest way to do
that is account linking.

00:23:11.790 --> 00:23:15.510
It allows your users to use
their own Google accounts

00:23:15.510 --> 00:23:18.660
to play your games or they
can link their Google account

00:23:18.660 --> 00:23:22.410
to your account
management system.

00:23:22.410 --> 00:23:24.360
To set up account
linking, simply

00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:27.920
just go to the Account Linking
view on Actions console.

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:29.760
There, you can define
what permissions

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:31.710
you plan to ask from the user.

00:23:31.710 --> 00:23:34.470
These permissions are
defined as scopes.

00:23:34.470 --> 00:23:37.530
For example, you can ask for
access to user's contacts,

00:23:37.530 --> 00:23:39.592
calendar, photos,
or other Google

00:23:39.592 --> 00:23:40.800
services they might be using.

00:23:43.340 --> 00:23:45.020
From a user's
perspective, they'll

00:23:45.020 --> 00:23:47.510
go through this familiar
Google sign-in flow

00:23:47.510 --> 00:23:49.991
to use their own Google account
or link the Google account

00:23:49.991 --> 00:23:50.990
to their gaming account.

00:23:54.610 --> 00:23:58.495
Creating this experience as
a developer is fairly simple.

00:23:58.495 --> 00:24:01.000
You just write literally
two lines of code

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:06.430
and use our sign-in helper
function to request sign-in.

00:24:06.430 --> 00:24:09.410
Once you do that, you need
to handle user's response.

00:24:09.410 --> 00:24:11.410
If the user goes through
the authentication flow

00:24:11.410 --> 00:24:13.840
successfully, you'll
receive an access token,

00:24:13.840 --> 00:24:15.940
which you can use to access
the resources that you

00:24:15.940 --> 00:24:17.800
ask permission for.

00:24:17.800 --> 00:24:19.210
If something goes
wrong, you just

00:24:19.210 --> 00:24:22.470
need to acknowledge it
and gracefully exit.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.400
One of the key differentiator
of Google Assistant

00:24:28.400 --> 00:24:31.070
is the fact that it's
available in various modalities

00:24:31.070 --> 00:24:33.680
and enables different
interaction types.

00:24:33.680 --> 00:24:36.170
Actions on Google APIs
give you full control

00:24:36.170 --> 00:24:40.244
on how to manage these
different interaction types.

00:24:40.244 --> 00:24:41.660
Let me quickly go
over what I mean

00:24:41.660 --> 00:24:43.930
by these different
interaction types.

00:24:43.930 --> 00:24:46.460
The first one is what
we call voice only.

00:24:46.460 --> 00:24:48.980
You can think of
your smart speakers.

00:24:48.980 --> 00:24:52.410
The whole interaction is
voice-based-- input and output.

00:24:52.410 --> 00:24:54.812
The next interaction type
is called voice forward.

00:24:54.812 --> 00:24:56.270
These are the smart
speakers you've

00:24:56.270 --> 00:24:58.790
seen in the sandbox area.

00:24:58.790 --> 00:25:02.300
Here, again, the primary
mode of interaction is voice,

00:25:02.300 --> 00:25:06.980
but it's enhanced with
visuals when necessary.

00:25:06.980 --> 00:25:09.490
The third interaction
model is intermodal.

00:25:09.490 --> 00:25:11.170
You can think of your phone.

00:25:11.170 --> 00:25:14.612
Here, you have conversation
and visuals intermixed.

00:25:14.612 --> 00:25:16.070
It can start with
the conversation,

00:25:16.070 --> 00:25:19.920
switch to a visual,
and go back and forth.

00:25:19.920 --> 00:25:21.850
And the last one is visual only.

00:25:21.850 --> 00:25:25.590
You can think of your phone
on mute as an example.

00:25:25.590 --> 00:25:28.820
Here, there is no
audio input or output.

00:25:28.820 --> 00:25:32.740
It's all about visuals and text.

00:25:32.740 --> 00:25:35.230
So let's go through an example.

00:25:35.230 --> 00:25:39.240
Let's say that a user is playing
your game on a smart speaker.

00:25:39.240 --> 00:25:43.020
And then, you want to
show them the image

00:25:43.020 --> 00:25:45.990
of their new monster evolved.

00:25:45.990 --> 00:25:48.810
We defined the image here.

00:25:48.810 --> 00:25:50.490
The first thing we
need to do is we

00:25:50.490 --> 00:25:55.380
need to check if the device the
player is playing your game on

00:25:55.380 --> 00:25:57.780
has the capability
to show an image.

00:25:57.780 --> 00:26:01.860
This capability is
defined as screen output.

00:26:01.860 --> 00:26:04.540
If the device has this
capability, great.

00:26:04.540 --> 00:26:05.790
We just show the image.

00:26:05.790 --> 00:26:07.860
But in our example,
the player is

00:26:07.860 --> 00:26:09.420
playing on a smart
speaker, which

00:26:09.420 --> 00:26:11.590
doesn't have that capability.

00:26:11.590 --> 00:26:15.690
So what we do is we ask the
user to switch to a device that

00:26:15.690 --> 00:26:17.500
has this capability.

00:26:17.500 --> 00:26:21.200
We do that with a helper
function called NewSurface.

00:26:21.200 --> 00:26:24.060
We define what capability
we are looking for,

00:26:24.060 --> 00:26:25.800
in this case screen output.

00:26:25.800 --> 00:26:28.220
We give the context to the
user on the smart speaker

00:26:28.220 --> 00:26:29.490
they are interacting with.

00:26:29.490 --> 00:26:33.814
To see your evolved
monster, go to your phone.

00:26:33.814 --> 00:26:35.730
And then, we send a
notification to the device

00:26:35.730 --> 00:26:38.820
that we want to get the user to.

00:26:38.820 --> 00:26:41.649
In this example, we say see
how your monster has evolved.

00:26:41.649 --> 00:26:43.440
And then, they can tap
to this notification

00:26:43.440 --> 00:26:45.356
and continue their
interaction on their phone.

00:26:48.060 --> 00:26:50.550
The final step as a
developer to manage this flow

00:26:50.550 --> 00:26:55.680
is you need to handle
the response of the user

00:26:55.680 --> 00:26:57.570
for our new surface prompt.

00:26:57.570 --> 00:26:59.550
If the user accepts
the prompt, moves

00:26:59.550 --> 00:27:03.810
to this new capable device,
then you simply show the image.

00:27:03.810 --> 00:27:07.660
If they don't, you just need to
gracefully exit and acknowledge

00:27:07.660 --> 00:27:09.715
that you won't be able
to show the image.

00:27:12.900 --> 00:27:16.120
Once your game action
starts getting traction,

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:18.012
you need to think
about reengagement.

00:27:18.012 --> 00:27:19.720
And we have multiple
ways in our platform

00:27:19.720 --> 00:27:24.920
to help you reengage
with your users.

00:27:24.920 --> 00:27:27.490
We literally have a section
called user engagement

00:27:27.490 --> 00:27:29.610
on our Actions console.

00:27:29.610 --> 00:27:32.590
There, you can opt into push
notifications, routines,

00:27:32.590 --> 00:27:35.080
and daily update suggestions.

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:37.480
If you opt into
push notifications,

00:27:37.480 --> 00:27:42.040
you will be allowed to send
notifications to your users.

00:27:42.040 --> 00:27:44.980
Obviously, the users
needs to provide consent.

00:27:44.980 --> 00:27:47.080
This is a really
powerful tool, so

00:27:47.080 --> 00:27:51.010
it needs to be used
thoughtfully and sparingly.

00:27:51.010 --> 00:27:54.170
You can think of routines
as actions chained together.

00:27:54.170 --> 00:27:56.980
For example, we have something
like I'm home routine,

00:27:56.980 --> 00:28:00.400
where you can bundle a bunch
of apps you want to trigger.

00:28:00.400 --> 00:28:03.280
And if you say, hey,
Google, I'm home,

00:28:03.280 --> 00:28:05.780
you might have Google
turn on the lights,

00:28:05.780 --> 00:28:08.140
adjust the thermostat,
tell you a joke maybe,

00:28:08.140 --> 00:28:11.370
and start your
favorite playlist.

00:28:11.370 --> 00:28:13.540
Daily updates is also similar.

00:28:13.540 --> 00:28:17.850
You set up a daily
notification that reoccurs

00:28:17.850 --> 00:28:20.320
every day at a set time.

00:28:20.320 --> 00:28:23.900
The user experience for
daily updates and routines

00:28:23.900 --> 00:28:27.940
is after your users engage
with your app and exit,

00:28:27.940 --> 00:28:29.710
they'll see a
suggestion shipped,

00:28:29.710 --> 00:28:33.130
prompting them to add your
action to daily updates

00:28:33.130 --> 00:28:35.560
or routines.

00:28:35.560 --> 00:28:38.800
Routines may not be that
suitable for gaming vertical,

00:28:38.800 --> 00:28:40.179
but something you think about.

00:28:40.179 --> 00:28:42.220
I'm just going to focus
on daily updates for now.

00:28:47.120 --> 00:28:50.990
This is what your users will see
if you opt into daily updates.

00:28:50.990 --> 00:28:53.890
After the user ends
their interaction,

00:28:53.890 --> 00:28:56.930
there will be a chip which
says, do you want me to send--

00:28:56.930 --> 00:28:58.980
in this case-- jokes daily?

00:28:58.980 --> 00:29:02.737
And if the user opts in,
Google will guide the user

00:29:02.737 --> 00:29:04.820
through setting the time
of the day when they want

00:29:04.820 --> 00:29:06.830
to receive the daily update.

00:29:06.830 --> 00:29:08.310
From this point
on, as a developer,

00:29:08.310 --> 00:29:09.393
you need to do two things.

00:29:11.900 --> 00:29:14.940
First, you need to handle user's
response to the daily update

00:29:14.940 --> 00:29:16.180
flow.

00:29:16.180 --> 00:29:18.820
If the user goes through
the flow successfully,

00:29:18.820 --> 00:29:20.410
you need to acknowledge that.

00:29:20.410 --> 00:29:24.610
If not, again, you need
to gracefully exit.

00:29:24.610 --> 00:29:27.520
The second step is you need
to define what you actually

00:29:27.520 --> 00:29:30.160
want to do when the
daily triggers arrives.

00:29:30.160 --> 00:29:35.020
Here, we set to trigger
the update intent.

00:29:35.020 --> 00:29:38.650
In the best dad jokes,
example the update intent

00:29:38.650 --> 00:29:42.325
would just send a new joke.

00:29:42.325 --> 00:29:44.200
Ultimately, this is what
your users will see.

00:29:48.740 --> 00:29:52.430
Lastly, I'd like to
talk about monetization

00:29:52.430 --> 00:29:54.260
options for your game.

00:29:54.260 --> 00:29:57.060
We just announced our
digital goods API here

00:29:57.060 --> 00:30:00.080
at I/O, that allows
you to directly sell

00:30:00.080 --> 00:30:04.150
digital entitlements using
Google Play infrastructure.

00:30:04.150 --> 00:30:07.160
This builds upon our
earlier launch this year,

00:30:07.160 --> 00:30:10.160
where you could use your
existing Play entitlements

00:30:10.160 --> 00:30:11.850
with Assistant actions.

00:30:11.850 --> 00:30:14.690
For example, if you
bought an audiobook

00:30:14.690 --> 00:30:18.620
or purchased a
monster in your game,

00:30:18.620 --> 00:30:21.860
you could actually use it
in your Google Assistant.

00:30:21.860 --> 00:30:25.950
What digital goods API does is
it makes the reverse also true.

00:30:25.950 --> 00:30:28.730
If you have a transaction
in your action,

00:30:28.730 --> 00:30:34.490
the same entitlement can be
used in your Android app.

00:30:34.490 --> 00:30:40.130
Let me go through an example
from our partners in Headspace

00:30:40.130 --> 00:30:42.950
to show you how this could
work on a smart display.

00:30:42.950 --> 00:30:45.600
For those of you who don't
know about Headspace,

00:30:45.600 --> 00:30:48.874
they are a company who build
products on guided meditation.

00:30:51.480 --> 00:30:53.820
So let's say that
a session is over

00:30:53.820 --> 00:30:58.500
and Headspace offers
the option to subscribe.

00:30:58.500 --> 00:31:00.980
The user responds with
an intent to subscribe.

00:31:03.820 --> 00:31:05.570
And the action shows
the available options

00:31:05.570 --> 00:31:09.450
in a very curated
and visual way.

00:31:09.450 --> 00:31:11.455
The user picks an option
and is handed over

00:31:11.455 --> 00:31:12.330
to the checkout flow.

00:31:15.330 --> 00:31:17.520
Here, if you enabled
account linking

00:31:17.520 --> 00:31:20.920
and the user already has account
credentials stored with Google,

00:31:20.920 --> 00:31:24.070
the checkout will
be very seamless.

00:31:24.070 --> 00:31:26.119
You just with a single
tap or a command,

00:31:26.119 --> 00:31:27.660
you'll have your
premium content that

00:31:27.660 --> 00:31:32.520
can be reused on the Assistant,
and also on Android apps.

00:31:32.520 --> 00:31:34.170
With that, I'm going
to hand it back

00:31:34.170 --> 00:31:37.620
to Thushan, who's going to talk
about implementing some best

00:31:37.620 --> 00:31:40.206
practices in your games.

00:31:40.206 --> 00:31:42.134
