00:31:45.030 --> 00:31:47.660
THUSHAN AMARASIRIWARDENA: So
now, we're going to pump it up.

00:31:47.660 --> 00:31:49.740
If you remember back
when Andy was talking,

00:31:49.740 --> 00:31:52.910
we showed the difference of
what sound design can do.

00:31:52.910 --> 00:31:56.930
These devices really rely
on music, sound effects,

00:31:56.930 --> 00:31:58.430
and voice.

00:31:58.430 --> 00:32:01.880
And we have some
technology that we

00:32:01.880 --> 00:32:06.290
wanted to showcase that can
help you pump it up quite a bit.

00:32:06.290 --> 00:32:10.190
You could, for example,
record tons and tons of lines

00:32:10.190 --> 00:32:12.980
with a voice actor and
get a sound engineer

00:32:12.980 --> 00:32:16.190
to add sound effects and
make some beautiful audio.

00:32:16.190 --> 00:32:18.840
Or you could use this
technology called

00:32:18.840 --> 00:32:21.050
SSML, which is Speech
Synthesis Markup

00:32:21.050 --> 00:32:25.712
Language, that allows you to
do it in real time in code.

00:32:25.712 --> 00:32:27.170
And what that also
allows you to do

00:32:27.170 --> 00:32:29.520
is to put variables
along the way.

00:32:29.520 --> 00:32:31.640
Now, we have this
static poem, but imagine

00:32:31.640 --> 00:32:34.940
if it said, thank you
for humoring me, Thushan.

00:32:34.940 --> 00:32:37.460
You could add
personalization to it,

00:32:37.460 --> 00:32:40.040
and yet still have that
dynamic sound effects and all.

00:32:40.040 --> 00:32:42.330
So here's our script.

00:32:42.330 --> 00:32:45.030
And we're going to
start pumping it up.

00:32:45.030 --> 00:32:48.020
SSML is just like HTML,
you just add tags.

00:32:48.020 --> 00:32:50.090
You wrap it in a speak tag.

00:32:50.090 --> 00:32:53.870
You put paragraph tags
when you have each line.

00:32:53.870 --> 00:32:55.370
And then, you can
start doing things

00:32:55.370 --> 00:32:56.900
like adding sound effects.

00:32:56.900 --> 00:33:00.890
And it's a simple audio
URL from your server.

00:33:03.800 --> 00:33:06.410
But there's more than just
text and sound effects.

00:33:06.410 --> 00:33:08.301
There's sound
layering, and that's

00:33:08.301 --> 00:33:09.800
what we're going
to talk about here.

00:33:09.800 --> 00:33:11.870
We have a tag called media.

00:33:11.870 --> 00:33:14.390
What media does is allow
you to essentially, make

00:33:14.390 --> 00:33:17.850
two or multiple tracks, and
then layer them together.

00:33:17.850 --> 00:33:19.730
This is our first track here.

00:33:19.730 --> 00:33:21.530
And we're going to call it poem.

00:33:21.530 --> 00:33:24.349
And it's going to
start one second in.

00:33:24.349 --> 00:33:25.640
And you'll see why in a second.

00:33:25.640 --> 00:33:26.900
We add another sound effect.

00:33:26.900 --> 00:33:30.480
And we even put a
little dramatic pause.

00:33:30.480 --> 00:33:35.280
And then, we work
on our music loop.

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:36.840
We call it music.

00:33:36.840 --> 00:33:39.660
We can control how many
times it loops through,

00:33:39.660 --> 00:33:44.250
set the sound level, if we
want it to fade in or fade out.

00:33:44.250 --> 00:33:48.720
And then, we use that name from
earlier when the poem ends.

00:33:48.720 --> 00:33:50.490
Let's run it for another second.

00:33:50.490 --> 00:33:53.910
And then, we have our
music loop itself.

00:33:53.910 --> 00:33:57.270
So altogether, we
wrap it in another tag

00:33:57.270 --> 00:33:59.330
called parallel, or par.

00:33:59.330 --> 00:34:02.140
And that runs both of
those tracks together.

00:34:02.140 --> 00:34:04.980
Now, what I showed you here is a
truncated version of that poem,

00:34:04.980 --> 00:34:09.201
but let's hear that example.

